revision.text:
The '''Violin Sonata No. 5''' in [[F major]], Opus 24, is a [[violin sonata]] by [[Ludwig van Beethoven]]. It is often known as the "Spring Sonata" (''Frühlingssonate''), and was published in [[1801 in music|1801]]. It was dedicated to [[Count Moritz von Fries]], a patron to whom Beethoven also dedicated two other works of the same year—the [[String Quintet, Op. 29 (Beethoven)|C major string quintet]] and the [[Violin Sonata No. 4 (Beethoven)|fourth violin sonata]]—as well as his later [[Symphony No. 7 (Beethoven)|seventh symphony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvbeethoven.com/Oeuvres/ListOpus.html|title=Beethoven's music with Opus number|website=Ludwig van Beethoven's website|accessdate=2014-10-18}}</ref>
==Structure==
The work is in four movements:
#''[[Allegro (music)|Allegro]]'' #''[[Adagio (music)|Adagio]] molto espressivo'' #''[[Scherzo]]: [[Allegro (music)|Allegro]] molto'' #''[[Rondo]]: [[Allegro (music)|Allegro]] ma non troppo''
The ''Scherzo'' and its trio are particularly brief. The entire sonata takes approximately 22 minutes to perform. The name "Spring Sonata" was given to it after Beethoven's death.
The ''Allegro'' movement is featured in the stage show ''[[Fame (musical)|Fame]]'' and in the syllabus of grade 8 of [[ABRSM]]'s bowed strings exam from 2016 till 2019.{{cn|date=August 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.abrsm.org/media/62976/violincomplete16.pdf|title=ABRSM Bowed Strings Syllabus 2016–2019|last=|first=|date=2016|website=ABRSM|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref>
While reviewing the [[Classic Produktion Osnabrück|cpo]] recording of composer [[Ferdinand Ries]]'s violin sonatas Op. 8 No. 1, Op. 16, No. 2 and Op. 71, Jonathan Woolf commented that the Op. 8 No. 1 sonata was heavily inspired by this work.<ref>{{harvnb|Woolf|2016}}</ref> ==See also== *[[Violin Sonata in A major (Beethoven)]]
